# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:unit-153
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Poetry anthology: first study"@en ;
  curric:slug "poetry-anthology-first-study" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupis explore 12 of the 15 poems from the 'Conflict' anthology.
  Pupils complete two lessons on each poem: one on understanding and one on analysis. Pupils
  study the poems in a thematically linked order so they can complete comparative and
  thematic lessons at key points in the unit."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of war poetry and
  comparison from 'Comparing poetry from the first world war'. In this unit, pupils look at
  conflict from a greater range of perspectives, and look at poetry from a wider range of wars.
  They complete more sustained and nuanced comparisons, and generate their own comparative
  points. They also develop and hone their expertise in writing comparative paragraphs and
  essays. This unit prepares pupils for the anthology's 'continued study' unit, where they will
  look at more complex poems and make nuanced comparisons across all poems.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-153-10 ;
  curric:id "153"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.074185Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry ,
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community ,
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-2-power-control-and-oppressive-regimes .

oakcurric:unit-177
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fiction: inner musings"@en ;
  curric:slug "fiction-inner-musings" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and practise emulating a range of different narrative
  voices. They explore narrative voice in 'Alias Grace', 'The Yellow Wallpaper' and 'Klara
  and the sun' before crafting their own narrative voices. At the end of the unit, they
  write a narrative with a compelling voice."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding and mastery of fiction
  writing from the unit 'Books that changed my world', as well as all of the other fiction
  writing units that they have studied in the Oak English curriculum. Here pupils refine the
  final elements of creating a compelling narrative by studying and emulating a range of
  powerful and unique narrative voices. This helps complete pupils' development of their own
  original narrative voice, and enables them to write compelling narratives that move and
  manipulate readers.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-177-10 ;
  curric:id "177"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.088508Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-english-language-gcse .

oakcurric:unit-3710
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Nineteenth century text: third deep dive"@en ;
  curric:slug "nineteenth-century-text-third-deep-dive" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore how Dickens presents 'A Christmas Carol' as a
  critique of dominant Victorian values. They first look at how he presents Victorian
  London, before looking at how he depicts poverty, suffering, wealth and status. They then
  look at what Dickens is critiquing in the novella."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of 'A Christmas Carol '
  from the second deep dive, 'a Christian parable'. In that unit, pupils saw how Dickens used
  religion as a way to present his social message in the novella. In this unit, pupils extend
  that thinking by focusing on Dickens' wider social and political ideas, as well as how he
  uses a variety of different methods to express those ideas. This helps them to develop
  deeper, richer and more nuanced ideas about the novella and Dickens' ideas.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3710-10 ;
  curric:id "3710"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.096793Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-173
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Shakespeare: second deep dive"@en ;
  curric:slug "macbeth-and-masculinity-the-struggle-for-power" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore the presentation of Juliet's agency in 'Romeo and
  Juliet'. After recapping Juliet's character and conceptualising agency, they look at five
  scenes through the prism of Juliet's agency. At the end, they learn how to use tentative
  language to write about female agency."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' deeper understanding of 'Romeo and
  Juliet' from the unit 'the integral role of violence and honour to masculinity'. In this
  unit, pupils explore the presentation of female agency in contrast to the presentation of
  masculinity in the previous deep dive unit. This deepens their understanding of the play, and
  enables them to write with greater nuance and tentativeness. This unit builds towards the
  final 'Romeo and Juliet' deep dive, 'the tragedy of societal expectations', where pupils will
  see another way of thinking deeply about the play.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-173-10 ;
  curric:id "173"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.107143Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-shakespeare-and-the-outsider .

oakcurric:unit-151
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Shakespeare: first reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "macbeth-lady-macbeth-as-a-machiavellian-villain" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and analyse 'Romeo and Juliet' by focusing on the role
  of fate. They start by understanding the play's tragedy and the concept of fate, before
  exploring key characters and themes in detail. They finally prepare and write an essay
  about the role of fate in the play."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupil's understanding of Shakespearean
  tragedy from 'Othello'. It also develops their understanding of a Shakespearean tragic hero,
  and enables them to see different conceptions of tragic heroes. This unit gives pupils a firm
  grounding in the play's key themes, characters and scenes, which sets them up for the deep
  dive units in year 11. In particular, this unit builds towards the first deep dive, which
  focuses on the relationship between masculinity and honour and violence.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-151-10 ;
  curric:id "151"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.117824Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-shakespeare-and-the-outsider .

oakcurric:unit-139
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Non-fiction: crime and punishment"@en ;
  curric:slug "non-fiction-crime-and-punishment" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop their non-fiction reading and writing skills by
  reading and responding to a selection of nineteenth century and modern non-fiction texts
  on the theme of crime and punishment. They practise summarising and comparing texts before
  writing an article and information text."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils' knowledge of non-fiction conventions and
  comparison from the the unit 'Women's rights across the ages'. Here, pupils start to explore
  increasingly complex texts and also develop more sophisticated and nuanced comparisons
  between texts. They also develop their summarising skills to show that they have comprehended
  what they have read, and develop their ability to emulate sophisticated skills from other
  non-fiction writers. This unit builds towards the unit 'Changing views', where pupils develop
  additional techniques to express themselves in non-fiction writing.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-139-9 ,
