oakcurric:unit-3742
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Spoken language masters: refining public speaking skills"@en ;
  curric:slug "spoken-language-masters-refining-public-speaking-skills" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop their confldence in delivering speeches. They first
  focus on finding a topic for a presentation, before building confidence and stronger vocal
  techniques. They finally deliver their presentations."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of speech writing from the
  unit 'The language of change'. Here, pupils focus more intensely on developing their own
  voices and build thier confidence and presence as a compelling public speaker. After
  completing speech writing in 'The language of change', pupils now focus on speech delivery.
  This unit concludes pupils' 11 year spoken language journey across primary and secondary by
  giving them the confidence and voice to speak their mind fluently in a variety of future-life
  situations.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3742-8 ;
  curric:id "3742"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.802197Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-171
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Unseen poetry"@en ;
  curric:slug "unseen-poetry" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils prepare for the unseen poetry in their Literature GCSE by
  reading poems, studying different poetry methods, and developing personal responses. They
  start by looking at ideas in single poems, before developing their comparative skills and
  writing comparisons of two unseen poems."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' wide reading of poetry and
  understanding of poetry analysis and comparison from the first and continued study units for
  their poetry anthology. Pupils now apply that knowledge by developing their own personal
  responses with less teacher direction and scaffolding. They also develop ideas and ways for
  reading poetry in their own time, which will enrich their future reading of poetry.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-171-10 ;
  curric:id "171"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.469387Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-152
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Nineteenth century text: first study"@en ;
  curric:slug "nineteenth-century-text-first-study" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore 'A Christmas Carol'. They start by reading
  the novella in full, pausing during each stave to analyse key scenes, characters, themes
  and methods. After reading the novella, pupils chart Scrooge's redemptive journey and
  craft an essay on the presentation of fear."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of Victorian literature
  from 'Sherlock Holmes: short stories', 'Victorian childhood' and 'A monster within'. In those
  earlier units, pupils read short Victorian stories and extracts from longer texts, but in
  this unit they read and analyse a full Victorian novella. Pupils now gain a deeper
  understanding of how Victorian writers used and debated key tropes and ideas in literature.
  This unit prepares pupils for the first 'A Christmas Carol' deep dive, 'A ghost story', where
  they start to think more conceptually and critically about the novella.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-152-10 ;
  curric:id "152"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.102042Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-exploring-the-gothic ,
    oakcurric:thread-nineteenth-century-literature .

oakcurric:unit-140
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fiction: read around the world"@en ;
  curric:slug "fiction-read-around-the-world" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read extracts from four novels from around the world, and use
  them to develop their narrative writing. In particular, pupils explore writers' use of
  structure. At the end of the unit, pupils consider their own use of paragraphs for effect
  and write an engaging narrative."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of structure from the
  unit 'Literary perspectives from the First World War'. In that unit, pupils started to notice
  and comment on writers' structural choices. In this unit, pupils become more conscious of
  structure, and start to make more complex observations about how writers use structure to
  manipulate readers. They start to use structure purposefully in their own writing for effect.
  This prepares them for the unit 'Science fiction writing', where they develop their literary
  analysis to focus on writers' language choices and their impact.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-140-10 ;
  curric:id "140"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.824713Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-english-language-gcse .

oakcurric:unit-179
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Writing masters"@en ;
  curric:slug "writing-masters" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils refine proficiency and flair as writers. Across fiction and
  non-fiction writing forms, they develop techniques that give them greater depth and flair
  in their writing. At the end of the unit, they write a narrative informed by emotion-led
  plot and detailed descriptions."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This is the final writing unit pupils complete in the Oak National Academy
  English curriculum, and it uses and builds on all of the knowledge and expertise they have
  developed in the previous 11 years. Now that pupils have developed their proficiency as
  writers across a range of forms, they focus solely on developing the flair and confidence
  required to make their writing compelling to all readers.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-179-10 ;
  curric:id "179"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.827954Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-non-fiction-reading-and-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-english-language-gcse .

oakcurric:unit-178
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Non-fiction: explorers"@en ;
  curric:slug "non-fiction-explorers" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop their non-fiction reading and writing skills by
  looking at non-fiction texts about explorers. They first conceptualise travel writing,
  before building towards making concise and developed comparisons between texts. They
  finally create a compelling account about a place."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' expertise in non-fiction reading and
  writing from 'teenage kicks'. Having already compared texts, they now start to complete
  increasingly precise and developed comparisons of viewpoints. They also coninue to refine
  their non-fiction writing by using all that they have learnt in the previous non-fiction
  writing units to write compelling accounts that engage, inform and entertain readers.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-178-10 ;
  curric:id "178"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.830989Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-non-fiction-reading-and-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-english-language-gcse .

oakcurric:unit-174
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Nineteenth century text: second deep dive"@en ;
  curric:slug "nineteenth-century-text-second-deep-dive" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore how the society the characters of 'Jekyll and Hyde'
  inhabit affects their interpretation of them. They first look at structure and the Gothic,
  before thinking carefully about how to use context. They then look at hypocrisy and write
  an essay about it in the novella."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowedge of 'Jekyll and Hyde' from
  their first reading of the text and their first deep dive. Pupils use their knowledge of the
  characters, themes and settings, as well as their more nuanced understanding of Stevenson's
  techniques, to apply context thoughtfully and tentatively to their interpretations of the
  text. This prepares pupils for their next deep dive, 'The dark side of the Industrial
  Revolution', where they will further explore how the novella's context informs their
  interpretations.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-174-10 ;
  curric:id "174"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.834977Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-exploring-the-gothic ,
    oakcurric:thread-nineteenth-century-literature .

